title: For Sale:  Smith and Wesson M&P compact
postcontent:
Up for sale is my S&W M&P9c chambered in 9mm. It is in perfect condition. I have found the compact model to be more accurate than the full size, but that's just my experience. It can nail the bullseye at 10 yards easily. I bought it January 4th from a dealer in Waukesha right when the "ban" craze started, so it took me a very long time to hunt one down. In fact, it was built/test fired only two weeks before I bought it. The barrel, take down lever, extractor, and slide catch have all been polished. It actually looks very good. I only have about 150 rounds through it. Since it's so new, it has the desired "shield trigger" that pre-12/2012 M&P compacts did not come with. It has the standard 3-dot Novak sights, picatinny rail, etc. Perfect concealed carry firearm. Here's what you get:

The firearm Two 12 round magazines- one flush base plate, one with the pinky extension Three palm swells (back straps) S&W Case Manual, test shell, NRA coupon, etc.

I paid somewhere in the $575 range, plus a $15 BG check, plus $35 in tax. Basically, I'm breaking even.

Since this is under my name, I require a photo/copy of your DL or CCW and a bill of sale. No exceptions unless its going through your FFL.

Face to face, cash only, no trades, no shipping.

title: For Trade:  My New Henry Golden Boy for Glock or similar
postcontent:
I live in New albany: I want a Glock/1911/Beretta/Springfield or other full size 9mm (or larger) pistol and I will trade the following: Henry Golden Boy (.22 lever action rifle) NEW IN BOX, comes with Brass Buttplate, Brass Receiver and the optional and coveted Brass Barrel-Band; also has the preferred Octagon Barrel with the gold engraving on both sides. It also will come with the Henry Model Cantilever scope mount that I ordered from the Henry website. Henry doesn't drill and tap nor cut scope grooves, in the brass receiver of the Golden Boy, so they make and sell their own scope mount just for this rifle. The scope mount attaches to the top of the barrel by removing the rear site and bolting scope mount to top of barrel. It's all new, it's all Henry. I intended on putting a scope on here, that's why I ordered their scope mount off of the Henry website. I went through some pictures of Henry Golden Boys with scopes and found the scope that looks great on this cowboy rifle...it looks right- so I ordered it. It will likely be here after the rifle is sold. I'll put it on something else I guess. Bought this for my wife's birthday, but it is too heavy for her, she couldn't handle it, so I had to go right back out and buy a regular Henry (the blued model with the round, not octagon barrel) that one is a little lighter and she can manage it. The wood is very dark and is beautiful on this rifle. As I mentiioned, I now have the regular Henry, the "blued" .22 lever rifle; the wood on this Golden model is so much nicer. I have never had anything like this rifle; the lever action is smooth like butter, the brass gleams all over like it's made of gold...it will be hard for someone to shoot it because it is so incredible looking. It came with a velvet "sock" wrapped around the brass receiver, Henry shipped it that way. It's a piece of art. It's not cheap, but there's nothing else like it.
I've got $695.00 in it, ..they are a little hard to find, Henry Manufacturing experienced a Hurricane and then a fire at the plant and production halted. I drove for a 5 hour round trip to get this one. Then ordered the scope mount from Henry. All total I've spent 695.00, I need 600.00 cash for it or 650.00-695.00 in pistol trade. I won't give it away. The pictures are with the Henry scope mount installed. I put it on so that you could see it installed. You can see how it sits over top the receiver without touching the receiver. It's ready for a scope. The Henry box for that mount is in the picture too. I will take the mount off if you want...and put the rear site back on if you like. Or leave it the way it is and give you the rear site in a ziplock. However you like. Email if you want 10 or so more pictures.
The pics don't do the brass justice...not at all. It's perfect. I have ammo for the right trade.

I have never had anything like this rifle; the lever action is smooth like butter, the brass gleams all over like it's made of gold...it will be hard for someone to shoot it because it is so incredible looking. title: For Sale:  Zastava M92PV AK Pistol BNIB w/ factory papers
postcontent:
BNIB. Zastava M92PV AK Pistol. 4 30rd mags (2Yugo,2 Bulgarian). 120rds Wolf 7.62x39 fmj. Produced in Serbia ( Former Yugslavia ) at the famous Zastava Arms Plant.This Yugo AK pistol, like other Yugo AK's, is unique in that it features a bolt hold open when used with original Yugo AK mags. Yugo AK mags are virtually identical to all other AK mags but they have a slightly different follower that will hold the bolt open after the last shot is fired.This rifle/pistol comes with 2 original Yugo AK mag and 2 Bulgarian AK Mags. Manual bolt hold open slot on the safety lever will hold bolt back regardless of mag and is unique to this weapon. To be clear, all other AK mags work perfectly with this rifle they just do not activate the bolt hold open feature.

Very loud. Big muzzle flash. Shooting it at dusk makes it look like a flamethrower. Shoot it after dark and the flash is blinding. Head-turner/crowd gatherer at the range everytime...

Have 2, selling one(BNIB) to cover the cost of SBR stamp and bells and whistles I am putting on the one I shoot currently.The gun is hated by gun-grabbers, so that is an additional reason to buy it.

title: For Trade:  RARE Steyr-Hahn Model 1912 w/ Nazi Police and Unit Markings, 9mm
postcontent:
For sale or trade, I have a rare Nazi police marked Model 1912 Steyr-Hahn that is chambered in 9mm Luger.  These pistols were originally chambered in 9mm Largo (9x23mm), but in 1938 after the German unification with Austria, the Nazis reworked 60,000 of these pistols for issue to their police.  They rechambered them in 9mm Luger (9x19mm).  All the serial numbered parts match (receiver, slide, and barrel).  The receiver bears the "Eagle/L" marking, which was the German police proof, as well as the "Eagle/N" proof.  It is stamped "08" on the slide, signifying that it was re-chambered in the P-08 round (9x19mm).  There are also unit markings on the lanyard loop.  I'm not sure if the unit markings are from it's WWI service, or from it's use in WWII.  It is marked "13 DR" on one side, and "249" on the other.  The slide is dated 1917.

It is in excellent operating condition with a worn finish.  Wood grips are in great condition with no cracks.  There is no rust, inside or out.  The bore is in like new condition with absolutely no rust or frosting.  It is bright with sharp rifling.  It shoots great and is fairly accurate for a nearly 100 year old pistol.  

Included with this pistol is a padded felt lined wood case, four original 8 round stripper clips, and 75 rounds of 9mm TulAmmo.  

Please send me an email if interested.  I have other pics as well.

title: For Sale/Trade:  FIE Titan .25 automatic pistol with 140 rounds of ammo.
location: Akron Ohio to Sharon PA and in between., Cleveland, Ohio
postcontent: REDUCED PRICE AGAIN.  Here is a little Titan pistol small enough to fit in the palm of your hand.  Most very small pistols without a hammer require that you carry with a round in the chamber, cocked with the safety on or draw and rack the slide to shoot.  I never liked to trust the safeties on these little guns and find the little lever is hard to push quickly.  This pistol has a hammer so it is possible to simply cock the hammer on a chambered round to fire.  And, with caution, one can lower the hammer without firing.  It is not a beauty queen but it is a reliable shooter.  Its very easy to carry and to conceal.   Fifty of the rounds are commercial full-metal jacket rounds.  The other 90 are reloads with lead bullets, which are cheaper for practice and less likely to penetrate walls in self defense activity.  They will expand while jacketed bullets usually do not.  It functions fine as I fired off the missing ten reload rounds recently with no malfunctions.
